1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,171
Companies want agents to reason across fragmented
tender records.

2
00:00:04,171 --> 00:00:08,805
But a hallucination, a superseded source, or an
unauthorized inference

3
00:00:08,805 --> 00:00:11,122
cannot become a business decision.

4
00:00:11,122 --> 00:00:12,975
TenderGraph lets GPT-5.6 reason.

5
00:00:12,975 --> 00:00:18,073
Evidence, authority, claims, changes, and human
approval remain separate and verifiable.

6
00:00:18,623 --> 00:00:20,666
This goes beyond summarization.

7
00:00:20,666 --> 00:00:26,284
Every answer is assembled from promoted claims bound
to exact evidence.

8
00:00:26,284 --> 00:00:31,902
The inspector exposes source, page, quotation,
parser, authority, URL, and hash.

9
00:00:31,902 --> 00:00:35,988
A commission recommendation is not a signed
contract.

10
00:00:36,538 --> 00:00:41,851
The question runs through a ChatGPT-authenticated
Codex session without an API key.

11
00:00:41,851 --> 00:00:44,507
GPT-5.6 composes only from admitted claims.

12
00:00:44,507 --> 00:00:48,049
The trace retains the model and Session ID.

13
00:00:48,049 --> 00:00:52,476
Fifteen code-owned gates reject invention, evidence
swaps, and scope contamination.

14
00:00:52,476 --> 00:00:55,575
They also reject leakage and incomplete output.

15
00:00:56,125 --> 00:00:58,346
I attach the official PDF.

16
00:00:58,346 --> 00:01:01,900
TenderGraph extracts eight hashed anchors without
granting authority.

17
00:01:01,900 --> 00:01:08,119
Codex compares a later public record with every
active claim and finds one corroboration.

18
00:01:08,119 --> 00:01:13,006
Six independent gates validate scope, evidence,
action semantics, and shadow authority.

19
00:01:13,006 --> 00:01:15,227
Nothing changes before human review.

20
00:01:15,777 --> 00:01:18,426
A later corrective resolution is harder.

21
00:01:18,426 --> 00:01:24,164
The original winner and loss explanation change,
while the award rule stays stable.

22
00:01:24,164 --> 00:01:29,903
The result matches the versioned reference and
cannot promote itself into official truth.

23
00:01:30,453 --> 00:01:33,878
This is a decision graph, not generic RAG.

24
00:01:33,878 --> 00:01:37,731
It connects versioned sources, evidence
dependencies, and reviewed claims.

25
00:01:37,731 --> 00:01:39,871
It also records explicit supersession.

26
00:01:39,871 --> 00:01:44,581
The same contracts run across Chilean, European, and
UK tender structures

27
00:01:44,581 --> 00:01:46,293
and common procurement formats.

28
00:01:46,843 --> 00:01:50,748
The enforcement is measured: 44 tests and 23 golden
scenarios.

29
00:01:50,748 --> 00:01:54,263
It includes 15 composition gates and 6 impact gates.

30
00:01:54,263 --> 00:01:57,388
The harness admitted 0 of 8 injected faults.

31
00:01:57,388 --> 00:02:00,512
This capture retains three fresh Codex Session IDs.

32
00:02:01,062 --> 00:02:05,664
Codex accelerated implementation, verification,
testing, and this redesign.

33
00:02:05,664 --> 00:02:10,265
TenderGraph controls what AI is allowed to conclude

34
00:02:10,265 --> 00:02:15,442
and how those conclusions may change when evidence
changes.

35
00:02:15,442 --> 00:02:19,468
GPT-5.6 can reason. It cannot become authority.
